}

real a, b, c;
pair A, B, C, F;

a = -2; b = 1.5; c = 3;
A = (a,func(a));
B = (b,func(b));
C = (c,func(c));
F = (0,1);

draw(graph(func,-4,5),red);
draw(Circle(A,abs(A - F)));
draw(Circle(B,abs(B - F)));
draw(Circle(C,abs(C - F)));
draw((-4,-1)--(6,-1));
draw(A--F,dashed);
draw(B--F,dashed);
draw(C--F,dashed);
draw(A--(a,-1),dashed);
draw(B--(b,-1),dashed);
draw(C--(c,-1),dashed);
draw((-3,-2)--(-3,5.5));

label("$m$", (6,-1), E);
label("$\ell$", (-3,5.5), N);

dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
[/asy]

Three noncollinear points in the coordinate plane determine a quadratic polynomial in $x$ unless two of the points have the same $x$-coordinate. Therefore, given the direction of the directrix, three noncollinear points determine a parabola, unless two of the points lie on a line perpendicular to the directrix. This case is ruled out by the given condition, so the answer is $\boxed{1}$.

resps:
 Let the three points be $A,B,C$ and let $D$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $O$ to $\ell$. Let $P,Q,R$ be the points of tangency of the circles with centers $A,B,C$ to line $m$. Let $O'P,O'Q,O'R$ be the feet of the perpendiculars from $O'$ to $m$, where $O'$ is the center of the circle with center $D$ and tangent to $\ell$.

