label("$P$", P, NE);
label("$Q$", Q, NE);
label("$R$", R, NE);
[/asy]

Then $O'P=O'Q=O'R$ by the Power of a Point Theorem, so $O'PQO'R$ is a rectangle. Also, $O'PQO'R$ is similar to $OPO'QO'R$, so $OPO'QO'R$ is a rectangle as well. Therefore, $P,Q,R$ are collinear.

Let $L$ be the line through $P,Q,R$. Then $L$ is perpendicular to $\ell$ and $L$ is the unique line with the given property. Therefore, $n=1$.

